WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.830 --> 00:00:09.500
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:15.549
This is a complete course for the CCNA, Cisco
Certified Network Associate.

00:00:15.549 --> 00:00:20.961
In this video we will look at one of the supplemental
resources I provide for this course, Anki

00:00:20.961 --> 00:00:23.010
flashcards.

00:00:23.010 --> 00:00:27.590
For most lecture videos of the course I will
provide a deck of flashcards that you can

00:00:27.590 --> 00:00:30.380
open in the Anki app.

00:00:30.380 --> 00:00:34.380
These flashcards will help you review and
remember important information covered in

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:35.910
each lecture.

00:00:35.910 --> 00:00:42.020
Anki is an example of SRS, Spaced Repetition
Software.

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:46.590
It allows you to create flashcards, as well
as import pre-made flashcards such as the

00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:48.260
ones I provide.

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:54.059
Anki’s algorithm schedules flashcard reviews
for you each day to help information stay

00:00:54.059 --> 00:00:56.629
in your long-term memory.

00:00:56.629 --> 00:01:00.770
You don’t have to use the flashcards for
this course, but I highly recommend that you

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:02.370
try them, at least.

00:01:02.370 --> 00:01:08.150
So, this is the Anki homepage, apps.ankiweb.net.

00:01:08.150 --> 00:01:13.110
If you want to really learn how to use Anki
well you can click on the Docs link up here

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:15.729
to read their documentation.

00:01:15.729 --> 00:01:19.720
But I’ll show you the basics in this video
that you need to use my flashcards for this

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:20.720
course.

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:26.939
So, let’s click on Download, and it brings
us down here where we can download Anki.

00:01:26.939 --> 00:01:33.880
It’s available for Windows, Mac, Linux,
as well as iPhone and Android.

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:39.799
I use Windows, so I’ve downloaded and installed
the latest version available for Windows.

00:01:39.799 --> 00:01:43.380
All versions of Anki except the iPhone version
are free.

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:47.740
The developer uses the sales of the iPhone
app to fund Anki’s development.

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:53.300
At the time I’m making this video the iPhone
version is 25 dollars.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:57.409
If you are using the Anki flashcards it’s
very convenient to be able to review them

00:01:57.409 --> 00:02:03.650
both on your desktop and on the go, so I purchased
the iPhone app myself.

00:02:03.650 --> 00:02:08.490
But if you have an iPhone and don’t want
to spend the 25 dollars, there is a web browser

00:02:08.490 --> 00:02:12.280
version of Anki available at ankiweb.net.

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:17.450
You can use this web app on an iPhone to review
your Anki flashcards without having to buy

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:18.780
the Anki app.

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:23.340
It’s limited, but good enough for just reviewing
flashcards.

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:28.520
Anyway, download the latest version of Anki
available for your platform and install it

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:30.690
like any other app.

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:34.319
Once you install it and open the app, it will
look like this.

00:02:34.319 --> 00:02:39.140
We could spend a lot of time looking at the
various functionalities of Anki, it’s quite

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:41.080
a flexible app.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:45.090
But for this video let me just walk through
what you need to know to use the flashcards

00:02:45.090 --> 00:02:47.330
in this course.

00:02:47.330 --> 00:02:51.630
And note that what I’m showing you in this
video is just my recommendation for how to

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:53.470
set up Anki.

00:02:53.470 --> 00:02:58.319
There are other ways you can set up your Anki
decks for studying, so feel free to experiment

00:02:58.319 --> 00:03:00.099
if you want to.

00:03:00.099 --> 00:03:05.540
Anyway, when you first open the app, you will
see this ‘Default’ deck here.

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:09.530
This deck will be here until you create or
import another deck.

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:14.310
So, let’s create a deck by clicking the
Create Deck button down here.

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:19.049
I’ll name it CCNA and click OK.

00:03:19.049 --> 00:03:22.920
Notice the CCNA deck has now replaced the
default deck.

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:29.129
We’re going to use this CCNA deck as a ‘parent’
deck, and import the decks for each day of

00:03:29.129 --> 00:03:33.030
my CCNA course as sub-decks of this one.

00:03:33.030 --> 00:03:36.659
Now, how can you get the flashcards for my
course?

00:03:36.659 --> 00:03:43.000
Let’s go to the first video of the course,
Day 1 – Network Devices.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.129
The link to get both the Anki flashcards and
the Packet Tracer lab files is in the top

00:03:48.129 --> 00:03:54.030
line of the description of the videos, where
it says ‘Free CCNA flashcards and packet

00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:56.790
tracer lab files for the course.

00:03:56.790 --> 00:04:02.790
The link is jitl.jp/ccna-files.

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:07.269
If you click on that link, you will be redirected
to this page.

00:04:07.269 --> 00:04:14.599
If you want you can just type in this URL
directly, sendfox.com/jeremysitlab.

00:04:14.599 --> 00:04:20.019
To receive the files, enter your first name
here, your email address, and then click on

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:21.509
Join.

00:04:21.509 --> 00:04:26.211
What should happen after that is you will
get an email to confirm your address, and

00:04:26.211 --> 00:04:30.840
after you confirm your email address you will
get the email with the links for the flashcards

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:32.260
and packet tracer labs.

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:39.410
As I’ve written above, if there are any
issues send me an email at info@jeremysitlab.com.

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:44.000
I check my emails at least once a day, so
I’ll get back to you.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.570
But, before sending an email please wait at
least 10 minutes.

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:52.889
I often get emails from people saying they
couldn’t receive the flashcards, and then

00:04:52.889 --> 00:04:57.410
a few minutes later they send me another email
saying nevermind, the email came.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:00.850
So, please wait at least 10 minutes.

00:05:00.850 --> 00:05:05.380
And note that, if you don’t want any further
emails from me after receiving the link for

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:10.740
the flashcards and labs, feel free to unsubscribe
from the mailing list.

00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:16.380
The files are all in a Google Drive and labeled
by the day of the course: Day 1 flashcards,

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:20.870
Day 1 lab, Day 2 flashcards, Day 2 lab, etc.

00:05:20.870 --> 00:05:26.460
All of the files are in this one drive, no
need to sign up multiple times.

00:05:26.460 --> 00:05:29.950
And actually you won’t be able to sign up
multiple times if you try.

00:05:29.950 --> 00:05:35.470
The email system I use will only send each
email to each address once.

00:05:35.470 --> 00:05:40.960
I highly recommend bookmarking this Google
Drive so you can access the files easily.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:45.690
For this demonstration I’ve download the
flashcards for Day 1 and Day 2, here they

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:47.600
are in the folder.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:51.130
To import them into Anki you can simply click
on the files.

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:57.430
I’ll import Day 1 by clicking on it, and
click close on this notification.

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:00.110
And then do the same for Day 2.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:02.710
Now both decks are imported into Anki.

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:08.580
Notice, next to each deck, there is a ‘20’
indicating that there are 20 new flashcards

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:10.509
in these decks to learn today.

00:06:10.509 --> 00:06:16.300
Here’s my first recommendation: increase
the maximum number of daily new cards and

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:17.560
reviews.

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:21.990
To do that, click the gear icon for either
of the decks.

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:27.030
Notice that the default settings for new cards
per day is 20, and maximum reviews per day

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:28.990
is 200.

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:33.410
I don’t want Anki limiting my new cards
or reviews, so I’ll just increase these

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:39.240
to 999 and 9999 and click on Save.

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:46.160
Now notice that the Day 1 deck has 22 new
cards and the Day 2 deck has 57, those are

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:51.970
the actual number of cards in each deck: before
the number of new cards Anki would show was

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:54.270
limited by that setting.

00:06:54.270 --> 00:06:59.110
Of course, you don’t have to increase the
limits, that’s just what I do.

00:06:59.110 --> 00:07:03.580
My next recommendation is to make the flashcard
decks for each day of the course sub-decks

00:07:03.580 --> 00:07:06.419
of this CCNA deck we made earlier.

00:07:06.419 --> 00:07:11.930
To do that, click on the deck name and drag
and drop it on to the CCNA deck.

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:15.270
I’ll do it for both decks.

00:07:15.270 --> 00:07:21.700
Now the CCNA deck has 79 new cards ready for
us to learn, but if I click the plus icon

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:25.500
next to the deck name I can see the individual
sub-decks.

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:30.390
So, this gives more flexibility in learning
and reviewing cards.

00:07:30.390 --> 00:07:34.440
If you want to review flashcards from all
days of the course at once, you can click

00:07:34.440 --> 00:07:36.810
on the CCNA deck.

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:41.030
But if you just want to review cards from
a particular day of the course, you can click

00:07:41.030 --> 00:07:43.740
on that particular deck.

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:47.530
For this demonstration I’ll just show the
Day 1 cards.

00:07:47.530 --> 00:07:50.900
To review cards in a deck, click on the deck’s
name.

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:53.210
And then click on Study Now.

00:07:53.210 --> 00:07:57.020
So, here’s the first flashcard we are shown.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:08:01.440
The ellipses in square brackets is the information
you have to remember.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:04.400
That’s the format I use for my flashcards.

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:10.370
So, think of the answer, and then to check
if you’re correct click on Show Answer down

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:12.090
here.

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:14.190
Now there are a few options.

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:17.600
If you got the answer wrong, you can click
Again.

00:08:17.600 --> 00:08:21.409
And note that it says ‘less than 1 minute’
above.

00:08:21.409 --> 00:08:26.220
That means Anki will show you the card again
within 1 minute, so you can try again to get

00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:28.340
the right answer.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:32.750
If you got the right answer but it was hard,
it took some time to remember, you can click

00:08:32.750 --> 00:08:34.370
on hard.

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:38.080
In that case it will show the card again within
6 minutes.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:43.399
‘Good’ is the normal option, it will show
the card again within 10 minutes.

00:08:43.399 --> 00:08:49.060
And if the card is easy you can click on that
and it will show the card again in 4 days.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:53.519
Personally, I recommend using only the Again
and Good buttons.

00:08:53.519 --> 00:08:56.339
If you answered correctly, click Good.

00:08:56.339 --> 00:08:57.990
If you didn’t, click Again.

00:08:57.990 --> 00:08:59.760
Nice and simple.

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:05.300
I’ll click on good, and now that’s our
first card done for now.

00:09:05.300 --> 00:09:11.370
Notice above the Show Answer button, the blue
number is now 21, those are the new cards,

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:13.730
and now there is a red 1.

00:09:13.730 --> 00:09:17.390
That card has just moved from ‘New’ to
‘Learning’.

00:09:17.390 --> 00:09:21.780
In Anki, new cards must be reviewed twice
in the first day.

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:25.630
The first time they will be included in the
blue number, meaning ‘New’.

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:30.190
The second time, they will be included in
the red number, meaning ‘Learning’.

00:09:30.190 --> 00:09:35.220
After that, when Anki shows us that card in
the future, it will be in the green category,

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:36.730
meaning ‘Review’.

00:09:36.730 --> 00:09:37.730
Let me demonstrate.

00:09:37.730 --> 00:09:41.700
I’ll just use the space bar to go through
these new cards.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:47.339
If you hit space bar the option in blue will
be selected, which is ‘Good’ in this case.

00:09:47.339 --> 00:09:52.910
And each time I select ‘Good’ on one of
the new cards it is moved over to the ‘Learning’

00:09:52.910 --> 00:09:54.089
category.

00:09:54.089 --> 00:09:59.399
After we get back to the first card and hit
Show Answer again, notice that this time if

00:09:59.399 --> 00:10:04.290
I select ‘Good’ the interval is increased
to 1 day.

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:08.000
That means tomorrow Anki will show me the
card again.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.980
If I answer correctly again tomorrow, that
interval will increase, maybe to 3 days.

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:19.090
If I answer correctly that time it’ll increase
again, for example maybe to 5 or 6 days after

00:10:19.090 --> 00:10:20.090
that.

00:10:20.090 --> 00:10:24.300
That’s the power of SRS apps like Anki.

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:29.450
As you correctly answer each flashcard, that
flashcard’s interval increases to help that

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:32.329
information stay in your long term memory.

00:10:32.329 --> 00:10:37.339
I’ll just use the space bar again to go
through these cards, and then this deck will

00:10:37.339 --> 00:10:39.279
be done for today.

00:10:39.279 --> 00:10:44.380
Tomorrow, Anki will show me all of these cards
again, because they all have a review interval

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:46.290
of 1 day currently.

00:10:46.290 --> 00:10:50.680
I’ll click on Decks to return to the menu
again.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:56.160
So, now next to the Day 1 deck there are 0
new cards.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:11:01.529
Tomorrow Anki will show me those cards again
for review, they will appear under the ‘Due’

00:11:01.529 --> 00:11:02.689
column.

00:11:02.689 --> 00:11:06.079
Before wrapping up, let me give a bit of advice.

00:11:06.079 --> 00:11:09.839
First is to not add more than one deck at
a time.

00:11:09.839 --> 00:11:14.850
For this demonstration I added both Day 1
and Day 2, but I’m only learning the Day

00:11:14.850 --> 00:11:16.360
1 cards.

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:21.200
If you add too many new cards each day, the
number of reviews Anki will give you every

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:25.649
day will accumulate and take a lot of time
to review.

00:11:25.649 --> 00:11:30.370
And make sure to do the reviews Anki schedules
for you every day, because if you miss a day

00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:35.149
or two that will also cause the scheduled
reviews to accumulate and it will be hard

00:11:35.149 --> 00:11:36.930
to catch up.

00:11:36.930 --> 00:11:41.540
My personal recommendation is to add each
flashcard deck after you have studied that

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:44.460
particular day’s lecture video.

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:47.770
After you’ve studied Day 1, add the Day
1 deck.

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:52.100
After you’ve studied Day 2, add the Day
2 deck, etc.

00:11:52.100 --> 00:11:57.430
Then do the scheduled reviews every day by
just clicking on the parent ‘CCNA’ deck,

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:00.450
rather than each individual sub-deck.

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:06.490
But as I said before, these are just my recommendations,
you are free to use Anki as you wish.

00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:10.980
In this video I only showed the basics you
need to review my flashcards, but you can

00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:14.700
do a lot more in Anki such as creating your
own flashcards.

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:18.950
I recommend spending some time getting familiar
with Anki and its capabilities.

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:24.610
It’s a great study tool, not just for the
CCNA but for anything.

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:29.410
By making and reviewing effective flashcards
you can choose exactly what information you

00:12:29.410 --> 00:12:34.649
will remember, rather than leaving it up to
chance what information your brain will remember

00:12:34.649 --> 00:12:37.520
and what information it will forget.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:41.240
Okay, that was a quick introduction to Anki.

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:45.550
You don’t have to use the Anki flashcards
with this course, but I highly recommend that

00:12:45.550 --> 00:12:46.550
you try them.

00:12:46.550 --> 00:12:51.420
I think you’ll find that they are very helpful
for remembering what you studied.

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:56.050
Anki is quite popular on the Internet these
days, so if you want to learn more about Anki

00:12:56.050 --> 00:13:00.930
and how to use it, check out Google, YouTube,
and Anki’s documentation.

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:03.060
That’s all for this video.

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:05.880
Thanks for watching.

